Incorrect. The only languages that lost inflection were Bulgarian and Macedonian (arguably two dialects of the same language). Also wrong, there are four; it has ainmneach (nominative and accusative), gairmeach (vocative), ginideach (genitive) and tabharthach (prepositional). The prepositional case is called the dative by convention.

>>175432531
Hopefully you're still around, sorry for the late response.

I'll copy a previous post I made:

As far as actual materials I've used, I'm not great at paying attention to my studies when I'm online because there are too many distractions, so I actually bought a couple of books (the "Teach Yourself Bulgarian" complete series, and the "Bulgarian Frequency" dictionary with the 2500 most common Bulgarian vocabulary words, both are about US$20 a piece on amazon right now). I also went to the store and got a notebook and a pack of 1,000 index cards.

The notebook idea is something I came up with on my own. Not sure if other /lang/ autists do it, but I have the entire thing dedicated solely to my Bulgarian studies. I take notes on things I've learned, write down some of my thoughts in Bulgarian, analyze translations I make, or just write about things that interest me or things that have been on my mind. I date every entry and go back and review and correct if necessary.

The index cards I guess are similar to this anki thing people in here use. I take some words that I'm either not familiar with, have trouble remembering, or are just very important and I need to know them, write the Bulgarian on one side, English on the other, and practice with myself. I keep track of how many I get correct and how many I get wrong. When I can get the whole deck correct without issues, I make a new one. Knowing around 1,000 words will be more than enough for you to be speaking with natives casually and understanding most conversations you hear.

The only two things you need to start speaking Bulgarian are a vocabulary and confidence to talk to other people without using a dictionary or translator. Once you have those two, everything else you'll pick up during the process.

One last thing, here are a few solid online resources:

https://www.bulgaro.io/learn-bulgarian
https://www.livelingua.com/fsi/Fsi-BulgarianBasicCourse-Volume1-StudentText.pdf

https://fsi-languages.yojik.eu/languages/PeaceCorps/Bulgarian/Bulgaria%20Language%20Files/BG_Bulgarian_Language_Lessons.pdf

Another thing I'm adamant about is listening to Bulgarian media. This is crucial to help you get down the cadence and speech patterns native Bulgarian speakers have. I'm not sure what kind of music or content you like, but here's what I use:

Bulgarian news:
https://www.novinite.bg

Almost 30 hours of Bulgarian hip hop music:
https://open.spotify.com/playlist/6MCtjUcFNAPMewGgQs9BMG?si=3aff5b85c3b24f28

BG cooking channel on YT:
https://www.youtube.com/@gotvenezanachinaeshti/videos

Expose yourself to the language as much as you can and enjoy it. It's a fucking awesome language spoken in a cool country by genuinely nice and interesting people. I feel sorry for anyone who hasn't experienced the world of Bulgaria and Bulgarian people, language, food, music, and culture. They're really missing out.

>>175441869

From a geological and meteorological standpoint, there isn't much in the way to stop cold Arctic air from sinking down the middle/interior of the continent. The purple is all relatively flat (though there are outliers). It's mostly the Great Plains getting hit hard.
The East Coast has the protection of the Gulf Stream coupled with the Appalachian mountains to help contain that warm air. The West Coast has the Rockies and various other warm water currents in the Pacific to keep them warm(er). Where I'm at right now, in Southern Ontario, is also being protected by the Gulf Stream and the heat sink known as the Great Lakes, but we're going to get very comfy soon once the wind changes today. but yeah, in general most cities in North America at the same latitude as European cities are colder in average, most of the continent doest have the benefit of the Gulf Stream and Mediterranean to regulate the temperature.

>>175401389
>what is a good kanji learning method?
the basic kanji are pretty different and hard to confuse, so you can just learn vocabulary

>Isn't learning kanji technically learning vocabulary too?
Sometimes, but mostly no. Most kanji don't mean anything by themselves I would say. The most basic kanji like 人、犬、日、彼、私、山、木 etc. all are a word by itself, but many words only have specific meaning in pairs of 2, for example I've never seen the kanji 発 used by itself, but there are a lot of words using it, like 爆発 (explosion)、発音 (pronunciation)、発表 (announcement)、発言 (statement)、発見 (discovery) etc.

The meaning of the kanji 発 is very vague by itself, and you can't really put into words what it means exactly, I mean there are lists like "departure, discharge, publish, emit, start from, disclose, counter for gunshots", but no Japanese thinks about this when seeing a compound word like 発音, they don't think "oh, it's emiting+sound, thus pronunciation", they just think of it as a unit. Sure they can break it down, but it's kind of like Greek or Latin words, when saying "monologue" nobody thinks "oh, mono=single + logos=word, that surely means speaking by yourself", instead it's kind of an unit.

Sure if you break it down you do notice it's built like that, but you rarely do break it down in practice. And in Japanese this logic applies to a lot of words.

Thus, you should just learn words, and the kanji will come naturally, you will start understanding them intuitively. Sure, if you ever come across two very similar kanji, like 鳥 and 烏 then do look them up and memorize what makes them different and look out for it, but for most words you don't have to, since they're pretty distinct.

Some words are just 1 kanji, but many words are either verbs, that also need okurigana, or 2-kanji words whose parts don't mean much in isolation

>should I use Anki for vocab + learning grammar?
I would say just learn vocabulary from Core2k/6k or some other decks and learn grammar from Tae Kim

Jort Kelder is niet echt onder de indruk van Jaïr Ferwerda en vooral niet van zijn mislukte programma Hai Society. “Toen is hij het gaan doen en ja, dan krijg je dat dus. Dan doe je iemand anders na.”

Jaïr Ferwerda bedong bij zijn overstap naar RTL 4 een eigen tv-programma: Hai Society. In deze serie dook hij vorig jaar zomer in de wereld van de rijkere Nederlanders, maar het kwam allemaal totáál niet authentiek over. De tv-maker kreeg bakken vol kritiek, onder meer van René van der Gijp en de televisieshow Promenade.
